user_request: A poem about stopping by woods on a snowy evening, with promises to keep.
final_poem:
# Promises to Keep

The woods are blanketed, each tree
draped in a shroud of white so thin
it shows the branch's own slow architecture—
all crotch and lean, the way a body bends.

I stop. The engine ticks its small
acknowledgment of road and ratchet.
Snow settles on the hood like memory
on a surface meant for other things.

There is a house behind this stand,
though only framework and smoke-sheathed walls—
a kind of promise drawn in steam,
the kind that vanishes with what it shows.

I have kept so many promises to walk
no further, to let darkness hold me here
with its thick wool coat and no-guests sign.
The woods are safe. The snow is mine

to study, each crystal laid against
the backwind window of my thinking—
six arms extended, turning toward the light,
each one a vow I once made not to fear.

And still I do not move. The engine
quiets now, its breath released
into the cold as something finally
satisfied with the way things are.

I will not tell myself the morning comes.
I will not promise that. For some promises
are not about the arrival—sweet house,
open door—are more the turning homeward,

the careful packing of one's eyes
from dark, the slow unstrapping
of a coat whose sleeves were never meant
to hold the weight of anywhere else.
